Currently there is no way to find an exact string using the _text ~_ or _comment ~_, etc, notations. Could we add another operator, something equivalent to 'contains exactly'?

E.g. _project = JIRA and text ~~ "this string of text"_ would return all JIRA project issues with "this string of text", with the individual words in that order.

We have a home built plugin that I'm upgrading from Jira 3.13 to Jira 4.1.
It access images using a *resource* entry in the atlassian-plugin.xml like this
{code:xml}
<resource type="download" name="my-images/" location="com/example/plugin/myimages"/>
{code}
which is the example in the [plugin documentation|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Downloadable+Plugin+Resources#DownloadablePluginResources-ExampleofResourceType%3AStylesheetreferringtoImages].

The URLs generated by WebResourceManagerImpl.getStaticResourcePrefix() look like this
{code}
http://localhost/s/519/8/1/_/download/resources/jira.bugscrubview:bug-scrub-plugin/images/reload.gif
{code}
Sometimes this URL is valid but sometimes it isn't.
When the URL is invalid, what it seems it really wants is
{code}
http://localhost/s/519/1/1/_/download/resources/jira.bugscrubview:bug-scrub-plugin/images/reload.gif
{code} 
But this is not what WebResourceManager generates.

Some users are having problems with the Escape Key and Comment Box in the new UI.
When writing a comment a user inadvertently or deliberately pushes the Escape button, the comment box will close and when it opens again the content is deleted.

A few possible solutions:

# Keep the content when teh comment is re-opened;
# Change the escape key with some global keyboard settings;
# Remove the function all together;

